This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Li Muyan, southern weekend correspondent

Southern weekend intern, Du Jiaxi

Editor in chief

For the past month, the Voice of Wuhan has been a mixture of sighs, depression, anxiety and panic. Their calls went out in all directions. At least 10 hotlines and thousands of counsellors provide them with psychological assistance.

On a maximum of one day, Wang Jing received 37 calls. An experienced psychotherapist can tell what's going on inside a person's head from their voice. In one girl's desperate tears, Wang Jing heard that she had been diagnosed in her hometown in Shanxi Province, while her boyfriend in Wuhan, who had a fever of 39 degrees, was still shuttling between the Union Medical College Hospital and his home waiting for an examination. They live in Wansongyuan, not far from the south China Seafood Market, to the hospital is only half a station. It had been a rainy day in Wuhan, and Wang Jing heard the boy's anxiety and despair.

Sometimes, some sounds are numb. Phelan, a community counselor, receives many of these calls. At first they are calm, but when the counselor begins to speak, they eagerly interrupt -- "you hear me first, " as if she were crying, in this special period has been a blessing, "crying is a kind of release. ".

A middle-aged waitress stayed behind in a hotel that catered to the construction crews at Vulcan Mountain. She did not return home to join her family, and a few days later, she developed a fever, cough, dizziness and weakness that made her a suspect. She couldn't get a nucleic acid test or a bed, so she's alone in a rental. In the night, Wang Jing received a phone call from her, a voice that was "weak, lonely and very desperate. ".

Wang Jing promised to call her daily from her private number to see how she was, as she called it, "the pact of life and death. " . This kind of one-time psychological assistance to ten to twenty minutes, private contact is rare. After a week of continuous phone calls, the other party gradually reduced fever, better, to go out to buy their own medicine to eat.

People in Wuhan like to say "it's annoying" . Yi Zhongtian, a scholar, once wrote, this is a popular saying among the Wuhan People, who grumble whenever they want to express genuine dissatisfaction or angry pleasure.

But for more than a month after the city was sealed off, the nine million remaining Wuhan residents showed great restraint. Lewlin, a psychologist who grew up here, said Wuhan's urban culture is flexible, optimistic and tolerant, and despite the anger and sadness, it has not added to the confusion. "Our people are very good people. ".

A young reporter for a local Wuhan Television Station runs to the hospital every day, often "on the edge" . He once saw a nurse crying in the ward because the patient had not been saved. "Every day in this city is a time of life and death, " he told southern weekly.

A 2006 study noted that 29 percent of those quarantined during SARS had ptsd and 31 percent had depressive symptoms. A survey in Taiwan found that about 9.2 percent of people had a more pessimistic view of life after SARS, and the prevalence of mental illness was 11.7 percent.

In an interview with China News Service, Author Fang Fang said almost everyone in Wuhan is traumatized, and she plans to seek psychological help herself. When Wuhan is unsealed in the future, it will be greeted with great joy -- as if people were finally free. "But the families of those who have died of illness are bound to be particularly sad, lit up with lights and one less person. Only they know the pain of losing their families. "

The first report of the epidemic situation of Dr. Zhang Jixian cried countless times, the patient died, materials, physical exhaustion, "a lifetime of tears. ".

Hongshan District's Mental Health Volunteers Yan Qun truly understood the meaning of this phrase, from the death of those around them began. She found that the Chinese are so used to avoiding life and death that most are unprepared. "I think most people in Wuhan are experiencing it now, the tears are dry; there aren't that many tears, because you have to live. "

"people who really know each other are reluctant to touch, " Yan told southern weekend. "It's like the knife just went in. You can't pull it out right away. "

Wuhan Sports Center Stadium, February 17,2020. (Xinhua News Agency, Xiao Yijiu / photo)

1
Every day just waiting, waiting for when it's GonNa Happen

1

###Every day just waiting, waiting for when it's GonNa Happen

When the news of the closure was announced, most Wuhan residents were still asleep. At 4 a.m. on Jan. 23, the film director, Wang Qiming, woke up early and afterward recorded how he felt: His body was getting heavier and heavier, his breathing more and more rapid, and "the last line of defense in his heart was completely broken. ". He wakes up his lover, who asks, is this your dream?

Xiao Jinsong's Zhongnan Hospital at Wuhan University Spread three weeks early, with the appearance of a SARS-like infectious disease, or even more cunning. Xiao, a neurologist, got his first call from a colleague inside the hospital, feeling isolated after the infection. People were confused, they didn't know what they were dealing with, they didn't know what they were dealing with, and soon they were going to see dozens, hundreds of health care workers infected, "all of our colleagues, falling one by one. ".

The 23-year-old girl Zhang Ziquan accompanied her mother to the hospital. The fever clinic was already full. Her mother coughed and had a fever, but refused to do a CT examination. She firmly believed that she would not be so easy to fall into the trap.

Shortly after the siege, my father began coughing. Zhang Ziquan's best friend is a nurse in a designated hospital, and his parents have been infected one after another. This feeling of being surrounded, let two young girls feel, "every day is waiting, waiting for when the attack, after the attack is serious or not serious, you do not know which day will die. ".

She refused to go to his home for the New Year, to call his grandfather: I must be infected, do not infect you. Mother blamed her, "big New Year's, do not say such unlucky words. ". GRANDPA said, "it's all right, don't cry. " GRANDPA began to cry.

On the 23rd, Hubei Province Psychological Consultant Association opened the earliest free psychological hotline. President Xiao Jinsong said, the first three days, every day there are more than 100 calls, close to 60 percent of ordinary people are at a loss. "All the access roads are closed, the subways, buses and ferries are shut down, and there is a sense of disaster, like a Catastrophe, like a moment of life or death, " said Wang Jing, a psychologist who works with the hotline.

There are people who feel abandoned, people who want a divorce, people who have other diseases and don't know where to look, people who are seriously ill and have run out of medicine. Xiao Jinsong's mental patients also face a shortage of drugs, he advised a depressed patient to cut the dose in half, with 7 days of drugs to last 14 days, not enough again cut in half, eat 28 days, "so you can get through this month. ".

Community workers were equally fearful, and a junior staffer called Pan Lan: I'm actually very worried, there are old people and children at home, I work in the front line every day, will bring back the virus?

In the early days, it was rainy all the time in Wuhan. Because of the ban on motor vehicles, Li Xiang and his father, who had a high fever, rode two bicycles from one hospital to another, weaving through a long line of screaming "I'm dying. ". A middle-aged woman can not be admitted to the hospital, the family even brought a bed, placed on the side of the cash register, let her sleep.

Lewlin had expected the siege to last only seven days, but by the sixth day of the Lunar New Year, the number of confirmed cases was still rising. This is the most difficult period for Wuhan people, the most helpless in the final analysis or no bed. Even with the psychological hotline, most of the requests for help are realistic. Psychologists do everything they can to find a bed, public or private. "A bed is a life at this point, " Lewlin said.

After standing in line for 12 days with a persistent fever, Li Xiang's father waited for the bed. During this period, the father alone in the bedroom isolation, the door placed a stool, food is ready to put on, people walked away to take. But the 86-year-old grandmother would not listen and would get up in the middle of the night and go to his father's room to touch his forehead to see if his fever had gone down. The day after father was admitted to the hospital, grandma also had a fever.

Zhang Menglin couldn't sleep all night and cried all the time. She found a bed for her mother, called the hospital, the community, the volunteers, tweeted, filled out all the help registers, and all she got was a waiting list. Although calm has now been restored, Zhang Menglin told southern weekly that he felt at the time: "there is no way to go ahead, it's a dead end, and no one can help you. "

To help a patient find a bed, Wang Jing called all levels of government, contacted all channels, still can not solve. She believes that if there are extra beds, they will be made available and that "there's really nothing they can do about it" . But she didn't know how to return the call, she couldn't confront herself as if she were "confronting a specific person, and this disaster happened to him. ".

2
"It is our right to grieve. "

2

###"It is our right to grieve. "

Even in Wuhan, the infected and the uninfected seem to be in two worlds. Mother high fever, coughing up blood, Zhang Ziquan no way to help, the same university counselor in Wuhan called, "Don't you go to the designated hospital check? " "Designated Hospital? " She felt incredible, "do you know how powerful people can go? "

On a rainy night, Zhang Ziquan's parents again rushed to the hospital, she saw the two wearing raincoat running back, hysterical collapse. She cried herself hoarse and thought of death. She made numerous phone calls for medical advice, and at one point called the psychological hotline, but no one answered.

The parents got home just before midnight, and the CT showed that the mother had been diagnosed. At that moment, Zhang Ziquan felt "relieved" -- "I felt calm all of a sudden, really calm" .

The unknown and the uncertainty almost drove her mad, but now it's certain. The family discussed, since they have been together for so many days, after simply no longer quarantine, do not wear masks at home, there is no disinfection.

There was a strange calm in the mood of the medical staff. At first, Xiao Jinsong received four or five calls from doctors every day for help, but as the outbreak intensified, it became less frequent. People are either in a "stress-resistant phase" and have no time to deal with their emotions, he said, or they choose to put up with it. He set his colleagues on a "hard lever" -- call him if their productivity drops or they can't function. It worked for a while that day, and then it calmed down again.

Wang Jing says the biggest problem is that the staff are tired, cooped up in their protective suits all day, and in some cases they just lie on the floor after their shift and have no energy to talk.

First-line rescue workers often experience "vicarious trauma" as a result of witnessing the suffering of others, empathizing with them and treating their trauma as their own. Xiao Jinsong in Wenchuan County for the relief workers to provide psychological counseling, rescue, we are full of vitality, after the end of the back to the troops, get up in the morning bugle sounded, no one got up, "psychological problems. ".

A nurse experienced the death of her parents. He described the pain as "indescribable, like watching a loved one die in your arms" .

The nurse continues to work, in a state of "resistance" to traumatic stress, a state in which the sympathetic nervous system is in a state of excitement, yet able to devote herself fully to her work, "enveloped in a noble cause, unable to grieve. " . If you go into the next phase of "exhaustion, " a traumatic experience will occur.

Xiao asked her if she would like to go home and rest. When she got home, she said, facing the House and the things her parents had used, she said, "what can I do? I might as well go to work. When I'm helping patients, it feels like I'm doing something. ".

"sorrow is our right. Sorrow is an emotional release to heal psychological wounds. We should cry bitterly and vent our emotions, " Xiao said, "We have to learn to express our normal emotions, even when we think they are negative, when in fact they are meaningful. "

On the evening of February 6, Dr. Li Wenliang Rescue, the news of death, Xiao Jinsong's colleagues in the Doctor Group was silent, completely "silent. ". As the atmosphere is too depressed, the staff member of the psychological guidance team quietly asked him: How to do? Xiao Jinsong said in the group: Let us mourn a bit, let us vent a bit.

Silence is what doctors do. "I'd like to, but I'm afraid I'll mess up Dr. Li, " Xiao Jinsong told southern weekly, "health care workers are a group of people who suffer when they are wronged. We are health care workers, and when you complain, it affects a lot of people. "

Grief stays only one night, the next day, the group active as usual, "talk about work, talk about some positive things. ".

3
"Don't treat them like patients. "

3

###"Don't treat them like patients. "

The thought of dying comes to you at some extreme moment. After Zhang Ziquan's mother was diagnosed, the hospital sent her home to quarantine, "it felt like I was left to fend for myself at home. ". Mother had a fever for nine days. She didn't want to take medicine. She said she wanted to die, but it was no fun to live. Zhang Ziquan did not respond, his father did not speak, as to everything has become accustomed to.

During SARS in 2003, a man in his late 50s hanged himself in the bathroom of Taipei Peace Hospital after the hospital was closed down. "When people are too desperate, they may commit suicide, or they may use a 'Carpe Diem' or 'last Hurrah' to ward off the feeling of despair, " said Yu Lingna, a psychotherapist.

On the afternoon of January 30, the director of the Department of infection asked Xiao Jinsong for help. A patient shouted to kill himself. Xiao Jinsong put on protective clothing, emergency access to the ward. The patient was so agitated, he struggled with the injection, and his arm was swollen. Unbeknownst to her, she had infected her parents, her husband, and her six-month-old child. She felt that she was the sinner in her family and had nothing to live for.

"It was hard, " Xiao said. "She didn't have to say anything. We all felt it. ".

She dare not contact with family, Xiao Jinsong advised her to contact relatives, classmates, for her emotional support back. Xiao Jinsong changed her perception of self-blame, "you are not a sinner, you and your family are victims. How can you have all the eggs under the nest? It is the whole nest turned over, we are all victims of this pandemic. "

But Xiao Jinsong also plaint, be blamed by family, blame of infectant"too much".

The resulting guilt can make it difficult to heal. Zhu Zhuohong, secretary-general of the Social Psychological Service Special Committee of the China Disaster Prevention Association, spent three years in psychological assistance after the earthquake in Wenchuan County. He had seen a wife repeatedly recall that her husband wanted to hold her and kiss her before he left, hit by a rock. She Long Thought of the kiss that did not promise, "there is guilt, there is self-blame, and even self-injury, suicide. ".

Earthquake is a sudden natural disaster, disease is slowly erosion of the human body, once a loved one confirmed, the family may be entangled, want to close and dare not close. "This kind of pain may be public, infectious disease-specific psychological trauma, or it may be quite complicated trauma, " Yu told southern weekend

"70 percent of our work is dealing with psychological problems, " the director of a shelter hospital told Xiao Jinsong

In another designated hospital, an old man insisted on leaving the hospital, refused to cooperate, tore the nurse's protective clothing, the police came. A doctor went to comfort, chat later learned that the elderly have the early symptoms of Alzheimer's, cognitive function has been degraded. After spending some time together, the old man and the nurses grew to know each other well and began to feel safe.

The doctor asked Xiao Jinsong, "we handle it right? " Xiao Jinsong told him: Patients respond well, is suitable.

Pan Lan received help from the CDC, isolation ward patients roar, crying, shouting "do not want to live. ". "Do you think a person who is in a mood swing would go and see it? " The hospital issued a pamphlet for dealing with psychological problems, but it was useless in an emergency

The doctor took the patient by the hand and said, we just have to hang on a little longer. "think of them as a normal person, not as patients, " Ms. Phan said. "This is more powerful than any technique. "

4
"Give him a happy ending or he'll never get over it. "

4

###"Give him a happy ending or he'll never get over it. "

In an epidemic, life and death suddenly become commonplace. A lawyer lost his 70-year-old father, who had been dragged by ambulance from hospital to hospital, without beds, to one place for examination and injections, and two days later to another place and injections. "human dignity is gone, and to be taken in for a shot is a debt of gratitude, " he cried over the phone with Wang Jing.

At this particular time, the body can not be placed in a funeral home. It must be cremated on the spot. Wang Jing said it would leave her family traumatised and require "gestalt therapy" -- as if the epidemic had passed, she advised the lawyer to bring his ashes to her hometown for a decent funeral "and give him a happy ending, or he will never get over it. ".

Funeral rituals in traditional cultures are good psychological healing. "without a memorial service and good palliative care, it will be difficult to heal the psychological trauma of losing a loved one, " Zhu told southern weekend, "A person who dies may have six to eight immediate family members, the most painful of which are those who may experience severe traumatic distress, post-traumatic depression and a risk of suicide. "

A friend called on her -- a man in his 60s -- to apply herself to a hospital. Pan Lan soothed her feelings. She called back three days later and was told that her father had gone and that she had not made it through the next day and night.

"When my father left, I couldn't even touch him. All I could do was kneel on the ground and keep kowtowing. " Hang up the phone, Pan Lan cried.

A young couple who had a 10-year-old boy and a 10-year-old girl died suddenly of a new coronary pneumonia. The wife locked herself away, didn't leave the house, didn't answer any phone calls from family or friends. The director of the Community Women's Federation went to Yan Qun and asked her for help. Yan Qun replied: She is now the best protection of their own, send good food, children look good, "let her stay in their own world for a period of time. ".

Lewlin saw a lot of people in Wenchuan County, and it was a month before the trauma started. Some people left Sichuan, go out on the streets; some people see through life and death, it is difficult to gain a sense of security.

In a way, Zhang Ziquan is lucky, the mother gradually reduced fever, Spirit is also better, the community arranged her to hotel isolation. But something in this girl has been changed forever, as if she realized that all the common sense she had ever known had failed, that your life was so fragile.

The first few days, she also planned to close the end of the city can go to like the TV internship, "still think 'future' this very high demand. ". Now, the girl who likes to dress up, eat, drink and have fun lies down every day, do not wash her hair, do not bathe, her father cooked something, she ate a little. Zhang Ziquan felt that he had not been "normal people. ".

A quote from Tolstoj might serve as a reference: "Life after death, and life after The Hours, are two distinct states of being aware that one is on the way to death. "

Asking for help online, a reporter interviewed Zhang Ziquan and asked her if she needed help. She replied, I hope you care for the more down-to-earth person -- the unconnected, the unconnected, the Carless, the unconnected, the unconnected, the unconnected, the unconnected, the unconnected, what about them

Whenever Zhang Ziquan expressed the pain of Wuhan people on Weibo, people came to debate with her, accusing her of spreading panic. "It's like breaking someone's dream. If I don't say it, then all those people died for nothing, " she told southern weekly. "It's like they're not a patient, they're not a person, they're the source of the panic. "

"They are all the people I pass by every day, people who line up together to buy milk tea, and people who argue idly while buying food. Now, we, they, have become 'disaster victims' , even 'dead' , people who chase funeral carriages crying and shouting. How can I accept that? " Zhang Ziquan said.

A heavy snow fell on Feb. 15 in Wuhan, covering empty streets and cars that had not been driven for a long time. Usually this time, Yanqun will be very happy, because you can go to the plum garden snow. One day she stayed at home to answer the help line, worried about the police on duty outside, staff, too cold, "must not catch a cold. ".

Zhang Menglin calmed down, and his mother was finally hospitalized. Her way of praying for fate is to "do good deeds" , many volunteers sent her medicine, she intends to wait 14 days isolation end, to sign up for the elderly to send food.

"They came to understand that death threatens everyone at every moment... " Tolstoj writes. "They also came to understand that disease should not separate people; Rather, it should provide opportunities for human beings to love each other. "

Wang Jing always describes how beautiful Wuhan is to soothe the callers. She invited outsiders to see the Cherry Blossoms in Wuhan University after the epidemic was over. Let's meet in the East L. Green Road and meet in Yellow Crane Tower, she would say to the people of Wuhan.

All the psychological help people know, the epidemic will end, but Wuhan people do not know when the peace of mind.
